2. Data and analyses

Snowshoe hare physical data were collected and made available by Knut Kielland and four co-creators at the Bonanza Creek Long Term Ecological Research (LTER) site in Fairbanks, Alaska. The data contain observations for 3197 snowshoe hares (Lepus americanus), collected over 13 years (1999-2012). Following exploratory data visualization, weight between male and female juvenile hares are compared with two-sample t-tests. Differences between groups are described by Cohens d effect size. The relationship between hind foot length and weight is explored by simple linear regression. All analyses are in R version 4.0.2 using RStudio version 1.3.1073.

Kielland, K., F.S. Chapin, R.W. Ruess, and Bonanza Creek LTER. 2017. Snowshoe hare physical data in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest: 1999-Present ver 22. Environmental Data Initiative. https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/03dce4856d79b91557d8e6ce2cbcdc14

Juvenile hare weights by sex and site

Figure 2. Weight (g) observations for juvenile hares of female. male, and unconfirmed sex by sampling site (Bonanza Black Spruce, Bonanza Mature, Bonanza Riparian). Gold (female), teal (male), and coral (unconfirmed sex) points indicate the weight observations at the three sites. The 25th and 75th percentile values are represented by the endpoints of the boxes, and the line and point within the boxes indicate the mean and median for each sex at each site. Data: Kielland et al.(2017).

At each site, the mean weight for male snowshoe hares is higher than that of females and especially larger than those of unconfirmed sex. Similarly, the median weight is higher for males consistently at each site. Comparing the sites, the Bonanza Bruce Spruce hares have a larger mean and median weight than hares in the Bonanza Mature and Bonanza Riparian sites. The data spread is wider in the Bonanza Mature and Bonanza Riparian sites than in the Bonanza Bruce site.

Comparing juvenile snowshoe hare weight by sex

Table 1. Descriptive statistics (mean, standard deviation, and sample size) for juvenile snowshoe hares, grouped by sex. Data: Kielland et al.(2017).

Sex Mean (g) Standard deviation (g) Sample size
f 855.39 292.25 200
m 945.86 333.22 163
NA 614.55 357.59 15

Weight (in grams) was compared for snowshoe hares of female, male, and unconfirmed sex, with other variables (such as site) not considered here. Male snowshoe hares had the highest weight (945.86 \(\pm\) 333.22 mm, n = 163; mean \(\pm\) 1 standard deviation) compared to females (855.39 \(\pm\) 292.25 mm, n = 200). The absolute difference in means is 90.47 mm, the difference in means is significant (Welchs two sample t-test: t(325.02) = 2.7096, p-value = 0.007093), and the effect size is small (0.2904674).
